<DOC><DOCNO> AP880920-0242 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-09-20-88 0315EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r f PM-BusinessHighlights 2Takes   09-20 0527</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Business Highlights, 2 Takes,0554</SECOND><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The Senate has approved a landmark free-tradeagreement with Canada, clearing the way for America's part inphasing out tariffs on $131 billion in merchandise that crosses theborder each year.   ``This agreement is positive for both nations and it is a boostfor the world trading system,'' Sen. Daniel P. Moynihan, D-N.Y.,said Monday as the Senate approved the measure 83-9.   The bill, which now goes to President Reagan's desk, would openthe door for a 10-year phase-out of tariffs and a number of othertrade curbs, but political problems on the Canadian side must beresolved first.</TEXT><DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Dart Group Corp., known for a series ofunsuccessful takeover bids for retailers, has offered to buy KrogerCo., one of the nation's largest supermarket companies, for $4.32billion.   Kroger said it was reviewing the offer, which was made Monday ina letter from Dart Chairman Herbert Haft.   The bid followed Kroger's announcement last week that it wasconsidering a $3.8 billion restructuring plan. The plan was beingexplored as a defensive move, partly because of the Haft family'sinterest in the Cincinnati-based supermarket company.</TEXT><DATELINE>RICHMOND, Va. (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   CSX Corp. says it will buy back up to 60million of its common shares and sell off two natural gas units ina billion-dollar restructuring that will allow the company toconcentrate on its transportation business.   CSX said it would begin repurchasing shares this week through a``Dutch auction,'' in which shareholders are invited to offer theirholdings at a price between $28 and $33 per share.   At $33 a share, the restructuring would cost CSX a total of$1.98 billion.</TEXT><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   An investor group trying to acquire Interco Inc.for $2.6 billion has warned the manufacturing company of``unfortunate consequences'' if it proceeds with an anti-takeoverrestructuring that includes asset sales.   Steven and Mitchell Rales, the brothers leading the takeovergroup, complained Monday that Interco had refused to communicatewith them for nearly two months.   St. Louis-based Interco said its restructuring could include thesale of assets such as its Ethan Allen furniture company.</TEXT><DATELINE>SINGAPORE (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Saudi Arabia is intentionally exceeding its oilproduction quota in response to the breakdown in discipline withinOPEC and in hopes of influencing an upcoming price committeemeeting, a respected oil industry newsletter says.   The Petroleum Intelligence Weekly said Monday that Saudi Arabiais trying to force other quota violators to stop overproduction.   The newsletter said the Saudis are expected to offer to returnto their quota only when other OPEC members do so.</TEXT><DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   New York, New England and Southern California havethe highest ratio of housing costs to wages in the nation and arefacing a severe labor shortage because of it, a new study shows.   The Harvard Business Review said that as a result of the housingcrunch, companies are abandoning big cities, unions are fightingfor wage increases tied to the cost of housing, and managers arerefusing transfers to places with high housing costs.   The study appears in the magazine's September-October issue.</TEXT><NOTE>MORE</NOTE></DOC>